2

Feb. 9, 1847. This day with the
assistance of an Indian I have
rendered into Mic Mac John 3:16.
thus "Nikskain kesalnugup m'sil
taselich, ay igenumuuih nauktach u'kwesul,
m' situen kedlamseduajul man
puk, apchu memajedou." Poor
as is this translation, it contains the
heavenly message. May He who has
enabled me to give the poor Indians
the New Testament entire in their
own tongue. Glory be to his name!

1 How do you do this morning? I am well.
2 What is your name? Where crossed out: do-y ? are you from
3 Where do you reside? How old are you
4 Have you a family? Are your parents living?
5 How many children have you.
6 one, two, three four.
7 How long have you resided here?
8 Three years and a half.
9 What you ask for the basket? bucket? churn?
10 It is too much. Will you take any left? No.
11 You are very close. Your are stingy.
12 Will you trust me? I will pay tomorrow
13 Come home with me, and teach me
to speak, and I will pay you the money,
and I will give you coppers, meat,
bread, butter, and cheese.
14 What will you ask to come and
see me every day crossed out: and for a week and teach
me?
15 When I can speak your language
correctly, I will teach the indian children.

6

1 I am glad to see you. Are your

  children all well?

2 Come hither. I want to whisper to you

  a little.

3 When will you come to town again?
4 Tomorrow? No, on Saturday.
5 Is your father at home? Whither has he gone?
6 Where (are) all the Indians?
7 The potatoes are all gone in my camp.
Bring some water, that I may wash
my face, and wash my hands, and
wash my feet, and wash my clothes.
9. The tea is hot. I burn my mouth.
10 I drink cold water.
I ride on horseback.
11 The horse drows the sled, and has
small bells around his neck.
12 Are you married? Is that your wife? yes.
13 My husband.
I am cold, tired am almost dead with hunger.
I hear you, come in, shut the door, sit down
